This Cougar has several beneficial features, such as its barrel and recoil system.  
A departure from the prevalent tilt-style system that dominates most semi-autos today, the 8045 F sports something different under its sleek, Bruniton-coated hide. 
A quick field strip reveals a locked-breech system utilizing a rotating barrel. 
The rotating design keeps the bore axis better aligned with the target, providing greater accuracy.
 What’s more, the mechanism reduces felt recoil and muzzle flip.
In addition to its compact size, all the edges on the Cougar’s non-glare steel slide are beveled to get rid of any sharp edges, which promote a snag-free draw while also preventing the pistol from shredding a shooter’s clothing, carry gear or hands with feline-like fury.
The Cougar feels good in hand due to the grip indent and being well balanced and points extremely well. 
The frame also contains a heavy-duty dust cover with an integral rail for mounting lights or lasers.
The Cougar 8045F has ambidextrous decocking/safety levers, making weak hand shooting easier.

title: For Sale:  1840's Era British Percussion Muff Pistol
postcontent:
Tried to make this little gun part of a package deal for a revolver. Revolver is gone, Muff Pistol remains. I've owned this since 1995. Bought on a lark in New Orleans. If memory serves its about circa 1848. Don't remember the type of wood. German Silver medallion on back strap. Dolphin Hammer. Drop Trigger, drops when hammer is cocked. Barrel is about 2" long. The caliber is thought to be about .50. Whole thing is about 6.5" long. The barrel unscrews for cleaning. Everything functions as it should. But if you want to shoot it I would refer you to a gunsmith first. Printed on left side is "Wm Jeffery" and below that "Plymouth." There is a proof mark on the bottom in front of the trigger. Has scroll work on both sides top and bottom. That's about it.
The story is that British women in need of protection would hide this type of gun in their Hand Muff. Which is a hand warmer. I've heard all the jokes.
Here's the deal. Make me an offer. I apparently overpaid for it or the market is very small. When this ad expires it will have a new home or it will return to my safe for all time. The worst I can say is no. And I will be nice about that.

I have up for your consideration a collector grade S&W 39-2 (9 mm single stack semi-auto) in great shape.  Forum members on the S&W forum have put the production date at mid to late 1971 but S&W can give you a firmer date if you call customer service.  Not sure if it has been shot. If it has, can't be more than a box through it considering the condition (notice no wear on the rails on the slide). Comes with clip, original box, manual, tool set (still sealed in the plastic baggy), extra clip wrapped in the S&W waxed paper, warranty card and manual. This 39-2 is one of the early ones that had the best features of the 39 and 39-2. One tell tale sign of a unmolested gun is the grip screw and these grip screws have not ever seen a screwdriver.
Blueing in in great shape.  What looks like blueing loss on the LH side of the slide serations is a reflection from my camera flash.
Only downsides are a very light scratch on the RH side of the slide and a light mark above the Smith (probably from sitting in the box and having the drawer it was in for 40 years opened and closed.
This is a really great collector firearm but it would also make a great conversation piece at the range if you were to decide  to turn this into a shooter.  
39-2s in this shape with all the original gear are going in the $800 range (+shipping) on GunBroker and the collectability of these is only going up.  Would prefer to sell FTF (following all IL and ATF laws) and have this collector grade 39-2 go to someone local.  If you want this shipped to you, it'd be an additional $40 shipped from my FFL to your FFL.   
Price dropped from 800 to 700.

title: For Sale:  Winchester 1907 WSLR .351
postcontent:
This is a Winchester 1907 chambered in .351. This gun was manufactured in January of 1913. The .351 is a hefty round used by police departments and prisons. This gun was a former police gun. It has the heavy butt stock and metal butt plate for expressing your feelings for the bad guy. I do not know what department this came from. John Dillinger had two of these, one in full auto. The magazine is a 10 round mag, it is a after market mag. Someone has replaced the front and rear sight with a Marbles sight. The original sights are easily found on Ebay. The bore has good rifling and looks good for 101 years old. This gun is perfectly functioning. I have not fired this one, but have shot my others. They are scary accurate and will take down a deer or coyote easy. 
Most of the bluing is gone, and there are cracks in the forearm. There are scuffs in the wood, but it is a lot better then most I have seen for a lot more money.

postcontent:
FNH Tactical Police Shotgun (TPS). Scabbard, 130+108 S&B rds, 2 Blackhawk Bandoleres, sling, everything shown $800 firm. 

The FNH has given a old piece of technology more than just an interesting facelift. The FN TPS is a essentially a highly modified and updated Winchester 1300 pump shotgun. The modifications & updates have resulted in a very modern-looking 12 gauge pump-action shotgun that "borrows" various tactical features from the AR-15/M16. This FN Tactical Police Shotgun features a Back-Ported 18" Barrel, the GLR16-S Super Recoil Reduction Multi-position Collapsible Buttstock, the M16 pistol grip, the M1913 picatinny rail, and iron sights (including the cut-down rear sight) that are utilized by all current "A3" type AR-15/M16's and M4's. Basically, FN has managed to design a pump shotgun with the same ergonomic and handling characteristics as the AR-15/M16. The TPS also features what FN calls an Internal Tactical Choke (ITC), which controls the spread of (lead or steel) buckshot loads. The TPS weighs 6.5 lbs empty, and has an ammunition capacity of 7 + 1. The FN Tactical Police Shotgun (TPS) is a well put together package. This weapon is extremely popular in both the law enforcement & civilian home defense market.

title: For Sale:  Larue Tactical PredatAR 5.56 (16") with Surefire Muzzle Brake
postcontent:
Brand new, never used.  No need to wait a year and a half for a new build/order.  No trade offers please.  Comes with all the extras, including the case, a surefire muzzle brake, RAT stock, stickers, extra rail strip and QD sling mount, an extra buffer spring (heavy duty), Dillo tactical beverage entry tool, etc.

The PredatAR® 5.56 is designed for those who are searching for a lightweight, ultra-reliable and accurate 5.56 mm NATO rifle for home-defense, competition-shooting or hunting. The PredatAR® takes the highly accurate OBR 5.56 “Lite” design, and lightens it in every possible way with the least possible impact to the accuracy that the standard OBR is known for. By contouring the barrel, skeletonizing the handguard, lowering and simplifying the upper rail, and using a low-profile gas block, we were able to reduce roughly 2 pounds from the standard OBR 5.56 rifle.

The barrels are lightweight-profiled with rifling in a 1/8 twist rate. The handguards on the PredatAR® extend out 14.75”, to suit a larger range of shooting styles. The zero-MOA upper rail provides plenty of room for weapon-mounted night-vision day/night combinations. Both the upper and lower are CNC-machined from billet aluminum for the optimum fit and consistency. Even though we lightened certain features, there is still additional material in strategic areas to achieve maximum accuracy. Each rifle ships with one, 3” long, MIL-STD-1913 detachable rail section.

Both models come with a 6-position LaRue RAT Stock and LaRue medium A-PEG™ Grip. The Bolt Carriers are hand-polished hard-chrome with staked carrier keys, with Texas-Spec Bolt assemblies.

Includes LaRue RAT Stock and LaRue medium A-PEG™ Grip, 1 Aluminum Magazine, 2 Rail Strips, and a Surefire Muzzle Brake. 

About LaRue Firearm Accuracy:

LaRue accuracy is known world-wide. The accuracy of each LaRue Rifle is proven at our 100-yard tunnel using match-grade ammunition. No LaRue firearm can leave the facility unless it obtains accuracy of less-than 1 MOA (1.047”) at 100 Yards. Each firearm ships with a copy of a 3-round group obtained from that actual firearm.  LaRue firearms are precision instruments that require discipline, training, proper ammunition and maintenance to yield the best results.

The SureFire high-capacity magazine for 5.56x45 mm (.223 Remington) ammunition is compatible with M4/M16/AR-15 variants and other firearms that accept standard STANAG 4179 magazines. Constructed from Mil-Spec hard-anodized aluminum, they feed smoothly and reliably due to optimal geometry, non-binding coil springs, and ingenious nesting polymer followers. SureFire High-Capacity magazines provide distinct tactical advantages: increased initial firepower in ambush situations; fewer reloads overall, which means less downtime and target distraction in a firefight; fast and easy magazine insertion, even with a closed bolt; less bulk compared to drum mags, enabling a normal weapon grip.
